0x00sec Reverse/Crypto Challenge 


CHALLENGE SUMMARY

A Linux x86_64 ELF binary, distributed as a base64-encoded gzip blob in a forum post, 
asks for a password and prints Access granted! or Access denied!. The binary 
deliberately has no ELF section headers, only program headers — breaking tools 
that rely on sections (like objdump -d by default) and pushing solvers toward 
either dynamic analysis or raw-offset static disassembly.


STEP-BY-STEP WALKTHROUGH


Step 1 — Unpacking the binary
-----------------------------
$ cat base64-text-below | base64 -d | gunzip > ch01
$ chmod +x ch01
$ file ch01
ch01: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV),
BuildID[sha1]=a32c469ee2e7d7e3c037022ddadc42dca8cebd0,
for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, dynamically linked,
interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, no section header

"no section header" is the first hint: standard tools like plain objdump -d or 
nm won't work out of the box.

Step 2 — Confirming the missing section headers
-----------------------------------------------
$ readelf -S ch01      # "There are no sections in this file."
$ nm ch01               # "no symbols"

Program headers (needed for the OS loader to actually run the binary) were 
intact, so it still executes normally — only the analysis metadata was stripped.

Step 3 — Dynamic recon
----------------------
Running it interactively:
0x00sec Reverse/Crypto Challenge #1 
by pico
Passwd: <input>
Access denied!

It reads a line via fgets from stdin and compares it against something internally. 
No crash, no buffer overflow behavior found with long/empty input — so this isn't 
a memory-corruption challenge, just an obfuscated comparison.

Step 4 — Strings pass
---------------------
$ strings ch01
Notable output:
fgets, stdin, puts, sysconf, exit, strlen, printf, mprotect
...
VJKURCUUYQTFKUXGTAUVTQPI
0x00sec Reverse/Crypto Challenge #1
by pico
Passwd: 
Access granted!
Access denied!

VJKURCUUYQTFKUXGTAUVTQPI stood out immediately: pure uppercase letters, fixed length, 
sitting right next to the prompt/result strings. That's the classic shape of a 
substitution-ciphered string.

Step 5 — Breaking the cipher
----------------------------
The forum post explicitly billed this as a "really simple encrypt algorithm." 
Tried a Caesar shift:

s = 'VJKURCUUYQTFKUXGTAUVTQPI'
shift = 2
print(''.join(chr((ord(c) - ord('A') - shift) % 26 + ord('A')) for c in s))

Shift of 2 decoded it cleanly to:
THISPASSWORDISVERYSTRONG
(joke/flavor text from the author — "this password is very strong" — doubling as 
the actual credential).

Step 6 — Verifying the password
-------------------------------
$ echo "THISPASSWORDISVERYSTRONG" | ./ch01
0x00sec Reverse/Crypto Challenge #1 
by pico
Passwd: Access granted!

Confirmed working.

Step 7 — Confirming the mechanism via static analysis
------------------------------------------------------
Since objdump -d produces nothing without section headers, the executable code 
was extracted manually using the program header info:
$ readelf -l ch01
LOAD  offset=0x1000  VirtAddr=0x401000  FileSiz=0x331  Flags=R E

Extracted and disassembled that range directly:
$ dd if=ch01 bs=1 skip=4096 count=817 of=code.bin
$ objdump -D -b binary -m i386:x86-64 -M intel --adjust-vma=0x401000 code.bin

Key logic in main (0x401205):
401231: lea rax,[rip+0xfffffffffffffc12]   # -> 0x400e4a  (outside the dumped code range)
401238: mov [0x404060], rax
40123f: lea rax,[rip+0x51fc]               # -> 0x406442  (also outside the dumped range)
401246: mov [0x404068], rax
...
40129e: add rax, 0x1234
4012a4: mov [0x404060], rax
4012b2: sub rax, 0x4321
4012b8: mov [0x404068], rax
...
4012bf: mov r12, [0x404068]        ; r12 = adjusted pointer #2
4012c6: mov rbx, [0x404048]        ; rbx = embedded ciphertext string
4012cd: mov rdx, [0x404060]        ; rdx = adjusted pointer #1
4012d4: lea rax,[rbp-0x410]        ; rax = input buffer (fgets target)
4012db: mov esi, 0x2
4012e0: mov rdi, rax
4012e3: call rdx                   ; call function @ pointer #1, args(buffer, 2)
4012e5: mov edx, 0x19              ; 25 (decimal)
4012ea: mov rsi, rbx               ; ciphertext string
4012ed: mov rdi, rax               ; return value of previous call
4012f0: call r12                   ; call function @ pointer #2, args(rdi, rsi, 25)
4012f3: test eax,eax
4012f5: jne 0x401308               ; nonzero -> "Access denied"
4012f7: ...                        ; zero    -> "Access granted"

This is the "twist." Rather than a plain strcmp visible in main, the binary 
computes two function pointers via runtime pointer arithmetic (base address + 0x1234, 
base address - 0x4321) pointing to code outside the simple linear region most people 
would dump first. Those computed addresses are then called indirectly (call rdx, call r12) 
to perform what is — based on dynamic behavior — a Caesar-shift transform (length argument 2) 
followed by a 25-byte comparison (0x19 = 25, matching the 25-character password length) 
against the embedded ciphertext at 0x404048 (VJKURCUUYQTFKUXGTAUVTQPI).

So the "simple algorithm" (Caesar shift by 2) is real and brute-forceable exactly 
as the post promised, but the binary hides where that logic lives behind computed/indirect 
calls so that naive linear disassembly of main doesn't reveal it directly — you have to 
either trace the indirect calls statically or just observe the behavior dynamically 
(which is the "double fun" — crypto-side brute force vs. full reversing — the author mentioned).

================================================================================
SOLUTION SUMMARY
================================================================================
Password: THISPASSWORDISVERYSTRONG
Cipher: Caesar shift, key = 2
Mechanism: Runtime-computed indirect function pointers obscure the comparison 
           routine from straightforward static disassembly of main; dynamic 
           testing or pointer-chasing both lead to the same 25-byte 
           Caesar-shifted string check.

